## Theoretical Explanation

### 1. Row-Major Memory Layout

In C, two-dimensional arrays are stored in **row-major order**.

This means:

```
A[0][0], A[0][1], A[0][2], ...
A[1][0], A[1][1], A[1][2], ...
```

are placed consecutively in memory.

Therefore:

* Horizontal traversal through a row is cache friendly.
* Vertical traversal through a column causes large memory jumps.

---

### 2. Why IKJ Was Fastest

Structure:

```c
for(i)
    for(k)
        for(j)
```

Innermost loop:

```c
j
```

accesses:

```
B[k][0], B[k][1], B[k][2], ...
C[i][0], C[i][1], C[i][2], ...
```

Both are stored sequentially in memory.

This allows:

* Efficient cache line utilization,
* Hardware prefetching,
* Reduced cache misses.

Additionally,

```c
A[i][k]
```

is loaded once and reused throughout the entire inner loop.

---

### 3. Why KIJ Performed Similarly

Structure:

```c
for(k)
    for(i)
        for(j)
```

Again,

```c
j
```

is the innermost loop.

Therefore:

```
B[k][j]
```

and

```
C[i][j]
```

are traversed sequentially.

Although

```
A[i][k]
```

moves vertically, only a single value is reused repeatedly during the inner loop.

Consequently, the performance penalty is small.

---

### 4. Why IJK and JIK Were Moderate

Structure:

```c
for(i)
    for(j)
        for(k)
```

or

```c
for(j)
    for(i)
        for(k)
```

The innermost loop traverses:

```
A[i][k]
```

efficiently across rows.

However,

```
B[k][j]
```

is accessed down columns:

```
B[0][j]
B[1][j]
B[2][j]
...
```

which causes repeated cache misses.

At the same time,

```
C[i][j]
```

remains fixed.

Thus, these orders exhibit mixed behavior and intermediate performance.

---

### 5. Why JKI and KJI Were Slowest

Structures:

```c
for(j)
    for(k)
        for(i)
```

and

```c
for(k)
    for(j)
        for(i)
```

Innermost loop:

```c
i
```

moves vertically through memory.

Both:

```
A[i][k]
```

and

```
C[i][j]
```

are accessed down columns.

This produces:

* Poor spatial locality,
* Frequent cache misses,
* Reduced effectiveness of hardware prefetching.

As a result, these loop orders performed worst.

---

## Key Observation

All six implementations performed exactly the same mathematical computation and executed approximately the same number of arithmetic operations.

The only difference was the order in which memory was accessed.

Yet, the slowest implementation was approximately:

```
48%
```

slower than the fastest implementation.

---

## Conclusion

This experiment demonstrates a fundamental principle of High Performance Computing:

> Computation is relatively cheap; moving data efficiently through the memory hierarchy is expensive.

Algorithmic performance depends not only on the number of arithmetic operations performed but also on how effectively the algorithm utilizes the cache hierarchy.

Two mathematically identical implementations can exhibit drastically different execution times solely because of differences in memory access patterns.

This experiment reinforced the importance of cache locality, spatial locality, and memory-aware algorithm design in modern computer systems.
